entry.title: OOP-VD: Ask the service if transcryption is needed.
entry.content:
Prior to this CL, the client of an out-of-process decoder needed to use

the VA-API in order to determine if transcryption was necessary for

protected content.



Unfortunately, as exposed by https://crbug.com/1435500, making LaCrOS

use libva directly may not work well. This CL moves towards removing the

aforementioned dependency on libva to help with this.



In order to tell the client whether it needs to do transcryption, this

CL adds an extra field to the response of Initialize().



Versioning considerations:



- Older client on top of a newer service: this CL shouldn't affect this

scenario because clients before this CL should not rely on the reply

from the service to determine if transcryption needs to be done.



- Newer client on top of an older service: this CL adds code to check

the version of the remote interface. If the version is too old, then

we fall back to the old way of determining whether transcryption is

needed. To determine the version of the interface, we re-purpose

OOPVideoDecoderSupportedConfigsManager to also track the version.

OOPVideoDecoderSupportedConfigsManager is a singleton and we cache

the version in it, so we're implicitly assuming that all

mojo::Remotes in one GPU process will all have the

same version.

notification when ReadingListSyncBridge::ModelReadyToSync() called.



When ReadingListSyncBridge::ModelReadyToSync() is called from

ReadingListModelImpl::StoreLoaded(), it's called before

ReadingListModelLoaded() is called, and it could reach to

ReadingListModelImpl::DeleteAllEntries() which means notifying deletions

to DualReadingListModel, which decrement the

DualReadingListModel::unread_entry_count_ and

DualReadingListModel::read_entry_count_ before they are initialized,

which causes the underflow.

entry.title: Various cleanups and behavior tweaks for menu layout.
entry.content:
* Add a `GetContentStart` method to centralize logic that was copied

multiple places, but not always precisely the same.

* When not all icons were the same width, we reserved the max width and

then centered all icons horizontally within that space -- but only for

`!config.icons_in_label`. Do this for the `icons_in_label` case also,

to prevent slight text misalignments there.

* Don't account for `config.check_width` in the icon area reservation if

we don't actually have any checks/radios to show.

* Eliminate `config.always_use_icon_to_label_padding`. This is an archaic

relic of pre-Harmony menus, isn't going to matter much in the Refresh

world with icons on most menu items, and isn't conceptually right

anyway; if we want that sort of effect, we really want to either boost

one of the horizontal padding values (e.g. the horizontal border

padding) or set an icon area min width instead of letting it fall to

zero. But really I think this is just confused and wrong.

* Respect `config.item_horizontal_border_badding` even for

`use_ash_system_ui_layout`.

* `config.item_horizontal_border_padding` was double-counted in various

places, e.g. in the right margin when

`!config.align_arrow_and_shortcut`.

* Slight precision improvement vertically centering icons against

labels.

* Miscellaneous other rewrites to shorten or clarify code.

entry.title: Relax checks in BlobDataBuilder::AppendBlob.
entry.content:
Previously referencing a blob with unknown size (i.e. a file

reference that was created without first getting the files metadata)

would always give an error. Now this is relaxed to allow such

references as long as the reference explicitly mentions which

part of the file should be referenced. In those cases it doesn't

matter that we don't know the size of the full file.



This then allows relaxing the similar check in

blink::BlobData::AppendBlob, which then lets us get rid of the

special File overrides for Blob::slice and Blob::AppendTo.



The end result of all of this is that blobs created out of existing

file backed Files will get information such as

BlobDataItem::file_access_ from the source blob rather than

having to repopulate this from scratch.



Besides being simpler code this also helps unblock DLP support

in https://crrev.com/c/4249117

entry.title: Implement resolving and computing of color records from interpolable
entry.content:
FontPalette



In CSSFontSelector, the binary tree of FontPalette values (representing

mix values) is already built. So we need to retrieve and apply values

from the @font-palette-values at-rules, just as it is done for the

non-animation case for custom palettes.



If there were problems retrieving data from the at-rules, for example

the current matching font-family does not match with the one in the

descriptor, we apply FontPalette that represents normal CSS value on

that leaf.



CSSFontSelector is also responsible for simplifying the tree. For

example, if at some point while traversing the tree we have the

situation where both of the endpoints of mix-palettes() operation are

equal, we can skip the mix-palettes node and use one of its children.



Then once we arrive in FontCustomPlatformData, we traverse the tree.

Once we reach the leaves we retrieve color records from the matching

font. From those we interpolate, scale or add two color lists on each

node of the tree.



Design doc:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1S9JJfjmBtmOVYyP9AmdTFsKfWetU7drsc2v7VSDQXoI/edit?usp=sharing&resourcekey=0-O21aXZY1z6MoClTB-cKmlw

Explainer: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1XMTrKH003KBOes6hxzI-3E7LTwp5YwFC-rnzoFpFrfw/edit?usp=sharing

entry.title: Implement mix value representation in FontPalette
entry.content:
Change FontPalette class to binary tree structure to represent

FontPalette mix value. Each node represents one of the following

operations: palette-mix, palette-add, palette-scale. The child notes represent FontPalettes that these operations apply to. [1]



The leafs of the tree are the "regular" non interpolable

FontPalette objects, inner nodes of the tree are interpolable palettes

with their palette_keyword_ type set to kInterpolablePalette.
